cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at| There are two 2@D Openings in this system, one for the "Simple" system, which is what I'm going to show you tonight.

The other is for the Complex version of the system, which is essentially a Multi 2@D Opening.

I'll be going through that after this course has finished  That something else is STRONG 16-23 point hands with ANY 4441 distribution.

These don't occur any more frequently than 11-15 4441 hands (probably less), but this is a hand type that is @Dnot@D specifically catered for by the 1@C Opening and always requires special handling, because Opener's suit rebids always show 5+-card suits.

Some Precision pairs overcome this by allowing 4-card suits to be shown by rebids, but I've never been comfortable with this approach and it really would change EVERYTHING else in the system (all the Asking Bids, responses etc).

Most Precision Pairs who abandon the "classic" 2@D Opening either take that route or use 2@D as a Multi, one of the options of which is a strong 4441 hand The 2@D Opening is unconditionally forcing for one round.

It is not unheard of for Responder to pass with a 7-card or longer Diamond suit and a Yarborough, but it is anti-systemic, not to mention masterminding, and you look a bit silly when partner turns out to have 4-card Diamond support and 6@D is cold <grin>.

Because the Opening is forcing, Opener must not forget that there is no guarantee of a decent trump fit anywhere and Responder may be very weak, so almost ALL of the low-level responses and sequences are natural and non- forcing.|
