Opener is now FORCED to rebid in a 4-card suit because they have the strength to handle developments.   This usually means using the DELTA Asking Bid, which we'll see in a few weeks.  


^b@2|fp|t-title|at|2D Opening|fp||at|^^^^|
at|The 2@D Opening shows ANY 4441 hand in the 16-23 point range, wherever the singleton is located.

Opener usually indicates their precise range and where the singleton lies with their next one or two rebids.

The 2@D Opening forces a relay of 2@H from Responder ^*bunless^*n Responder holds one of the following hand-types:
^c@2
2@d -  2@s/3@c/3@d/3@h  ^h0-4  hcp   a 6-card or longer suit   Responder bids it as cheaply as possible (^*bnot^*n 2@h)
2@d -  2NT ^h14+ hcp   at least 4-cards in BOTH Majors
2@d -  3@s ^h14+ hcp   at least 4-cards in Spades and one or both ^*bMinors^*n
2@d -  3NT ^h14+ hcp   at least 4-cards in BOTH ^*bMinors^*n
^b@2
With long Hearts and 0-4 points Responder bids 3@H immediately rather than the 2@H Relay.

The "rescue" bids (2@S, 3@C, 3@D and 3@H) serve as a warning to Opener, especially if Responder has found their singleton suit (in which case they'll usually pass), but Opener may bid on if this has hit a 4-card suit in their hand.

The 2NT, 3@S and 3NT Responses are immediately slam invitational, since we're GUARANTEED a fit somewhere and KNOW we have 30+ HCP between the two hands.  


With ANY holding  ^*bnot shown above^*n, Responder MUST bid 2@H over the 2@D Opening.|
