cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  So what do we do in the event of interference? Firstly, let's look when Opps intervene immediately over the 2@D Opening.

^c(1) ^dw@2ith any hand that would normally make the 2@H Relay or one of the long-weak-suit responses, Responder simply ^*bpasses^*n (but see below).

^c(2) ^dwith a 14+ 2-suited hand that would normally have bid  2NT, 3@S or 3NT,  Responder ^*bDoubles^*n.

^c(3) ^dw@2ith a LIMITED (0-7) hand with two 4-card suits (NOT Opps suit), Responder bids their CHEAPEST 4-card suit we can afford as we know we'll have a fit somewhere (4-card includes 4+ cards, obviously).  So
^b@2
If Responder PASSES over the interference, Opener will tend to Double if the interference is in their singleton suit (ie: takeout),  ^*bOR^*n  bid their cheapest 4-card suit otherwise.
^b@2
with 20-23 points they might double for takeout even with a 4-card holding in Opps' suit, or might bid the suit below their singleton if it's obvious this is NOT their cheapest 4-card suit (ie: more than 2 steps over the interference). So:

^c2@D  -  (2@H)  -  Pass  -  (Pass)
|n^|8|at|
^c3@C      
|n^|8|at|
is definitely 20-23 HCP with a singleton Diamond, because Opener could have bid 2@S with a 16-19 hand of the same type.

