cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  If Responder DOUBLES over the interference (showing 14+) Opener has the option of passing at favourable vulnerability, but will normally bid the suit below their singleton.

Responder now makes an Eta Ask (or sets the suit inviting cue - bids if no Asking Bids in use).    So

^c2@D  -  (2@H)  -  X(14+ 2-suited)  -  3@H(singleton Spade)  -  4@C         the 4@c  sets the suit.

^cOne thin@2g in passing.  It won't have escaped your notice that 2-suited hands with HEARTS and a Minor are not catered for in the scheme I've outlined.  That's just tough.   There's no space to include that hand-type.

HOWEVER - If 2nd-in-hand over the 2@D Opening bids something and Responder HAS a 14+ hand with hearts and a Minor, they can now still Double to show a 14+ 2-suited hand because come what may Opener will bid the suit below their singleton over the double and Responder can now set whichever suit we have a fit in, as trumps.

^b@2If, over the interference, Responder bids a suit (showing 2-suited 0-7), Opener bids naturally, either (if Responder has hit their singleton) bidding the next suit up  ^*bOR^*n  passing with a minimum hand (and a fit)  ^*bOR^*n   raising / bidding game with a fit and a mid/upper range hand.

With a 4-card holding in Opps' suit and no fit, Opener can bid NT's if it's cheaper than bidding the next suit.  So

^c2@D  -  (2@H)  -  2@S(0-7, 2-suited, @S and another)  -  2NT       the 2NT just shows a singleton Spade

now Responder just shows their second suit.  All the bids, once Responder bids a suit, are essentially natural and non-forcing.      However - if Opps Double and Responder passes, Opener redoubles with a singleton in the suit bid  ^*bOR^*n  bids the next suit up, without.

That covers interference over the 2@D Opening.|
