cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Now let's turn our attention to interference over the 2@H Relay (or one of the 14+ Responses).

^c@.   If Responder bid 2@H and Opps Double, a redouble by Opener shows a singleton Heart.

^c@.   Similarly, if Opps bid a suit, a Double by Opener is for takeout, showing a singleton in their suit.

^c@.   In @2one of those situations, If Opener PASSES over the interference, it implies a 4-card holding in Hearts (over a double of 2@H)  OR  a 4-card holding in the suit bid by Opps.

^c@.   with an upper range hand (20-23), Opener can bid their cheapest 4-card suit over Opps' bid, or perhaps even bid 2/3NT with a maximum hand and a 4-card holding in Opps' suit.  (but bear in mind that responder hasn't promised ANYTHING as yet). 
^b@2
If Opener passes over the interference, then a Double by Responder is essentially for takeout, but showing values in the knowledge that Opener probably has a 4-card holding in Opps' suit and may well pass for penalties.

If Responder has shown a long-weak suit variety that has hit Opener's singleton, and Opps interfere, Opener will tend to pass, but can obviously compete or bid game if they have a 4-card fit for Responder's suit.

If Responder has shown one of the 14+ hand-types (2NT, 3@S or 3NT), then Opener bids the cheapest potential (or known) fit, or can bid Opps' suit with a KNOWN double fit   eg:  

^c2@D  -  3@S(@S+Minor)  -  (4@H)  -  ???     now Opener might bid 5@H with a Singleton @H.|
